U.S. Gasoline Use Rises 2.2% From Previous Week, MasterCard Says

-- B y   B a r b a r a   J   P o w e l l
-- 
2011-10-18T18:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-18/u-s-gasoline-use-rises-2-2-from-previous-week-mastercard-says.html
U.S. gasoline consumption increased
2.2 percent last week from a week earlier, according to
 MasterCard Inc. (MA)   Motorists bought 8.975 million barrels a day in the week
ended Oct. 14, the second-biggest payments network company said
in its SpendingPulse report, up from 8.79 million the previous
week. A year earlier demand was 9.26 million barrels.  The average pump price rose 2 cents to $3.42 a gallon, 21
percent higher than a year earlier. It was the first increase in
five weeks.  Averaged over four weeks, gasoline use was 2.8 percent
below a year earlier. It was the 30th week in a row that demand
fell on that basis, according to SpendingPulse data.  Gasoline demand peaked this year at 9.56 million barrels a
day in the week ended July 1 as motorists filled their tanks
before the July 4 holiday weekend. The lowest level of
consumption occurred in the week ended Feb. 11 when consumers
bought 8.47 million barrels a day.  The report from Purchase, New York-based MasterCard is
assembled by MasterCard Advisors, the companyâ€™s consulting arm.
The information is based on credit-card swipes and cash and
check payments at about 140,000 U.S. gasoline stations.  Visa Inc. (V)  is the biggest payments network company by
transactions processed.  To contact the reporter on this story:
